title: For Sale/Trade:  ~410 pieces once fired 45 acp, LPP
postcontent:
I have decided to go with small pistol primered 45 auto brass so I don't have to change primer mechanisms on my progressive press.  I think everyone can agree that nobody wants to have two types of primers in the same type of brass, so I've decided to get rid of my brass with large primers.  This is the most common configuration of 45 acp, so it will most likely go with what you already have.

Anyway, this brass is mixed headstamped and has been sized, deprimed and tumbled after being ONCE fired.  I'd like to trade for reloading supplies, lots of possibilities there.  I could also sell outright.  Bullets, brass, primers, powders (only unopened powders please).  I'll be reasonable...  I don't expect 400 45-70 brass for my 45 auto or anything ridiculous.

Here are the calibers for which I reload, which may help you in making an offer.  

45 acp
45-70... really want some brass for this.
308
357 magnum
38 sp.

9mm

Gun comes with original box, manual, test fired target at factory, 2 magazines, takedown tool, brush, original German P7 holster, original HK flashlight, knife and sticker. You won't find any deal for cheap like this. The NIB P7 runs over $1400-1500 with no extras like mine.

More of interesting history of P7:

***Heckler & Koch P7***

Type	Semi-automatic pistol
Place of origin	 West Germany
Designer	Helmut Weldle
Designed	1976
Manufacturer	Heckler & Koch
Produced	1979–2008

Specifications
Weight : 785 g (27.7 oz)
Length: 166 mm (6.5 in)
Barrel length: 105 mm (4.1 in)
Width: 29 mm (1.1 in)
Height: 127 mm (5.0 in)
Cartridge: 9x19mm Parabellum
Action: Gas-delayed blowback
Muzzle velocity: 351 m/s (1,152 ft/s)
Feed system: 8-round box magazine
Sights: Front blade, rear notch,148 mm (5.8 in) sight radius
The P7 is a German 9mm semi-automatic pistol designed by Helmut Weldle and produced by Heckler & Koch GmbH (H&K) of Oberndorf am Neckar. It was revealed to the public for the first time in 1976 as the PSP (Polizei-Selbstlade-Pistole—“police self-loading pistol”)

The decision to equip West German police with an advanced 9mm service pistol and replace existing 7.65mm-caliber weapons was prompted after the 1972 Munich Olympics Massacre. The new firearm was to meet the following requirements: chamber the 9x19mm Parabellum cartridge, weigh no more than 1,000 g (35 oz), the pistol's dimensions would not exceed 180 x 130 x 34 mm, it should have a muzzle energy of no less than 500 J and a service life of at least 10,000 rounds. The pistol was also to be fully ambidextrous, safe to carry with a loaded chamber and able to be quickly drawn and ready to fire instantly. As a result of a competitive bid the German police forces selected three different pistols into service: the Swiss SIG-Sauer P225 (designated the P6) and two German designs—the P7 (officially designated the PSP) and the Walther P5.
Series production of the P7 started in 1979. Shortly after, the pistol was adopted by the German Federal Police's counter-terrorism unit (GSG 9) and the German Army's special forces formations.The P7 was produced primarily by H&K but also under license by the Greek defense firm Hellenic Arms Industry[citation needed] as well as in Mexico by the Departamento de Industria Militar (DIM), as a sidearm for general officers and staff. The pistol was also exported to several countries

A schematic of the P7's gas-delayed blowback system.
The P7 is a semi-automatic, blowback-operated firearm. It features a unique gas-delayed blowback locking system modeled on the Swiss Pistole 47 W+F (Waffenfabrik Bern) prototype pistol (and ultimately on the Barnitzke system first used in the Volkssturmgewehr 1-5, which used gas pressures from the ignited cartridge and fed them through a small port in the barrel (in front of the chamber) to retard the rearward motion of the slide. This is accomplished by means of a piston contained inside of a cylinder located under the barrel that opposes the rearward motion of the slide until the gas pressure has declined—after the bullet has left the barrel—hence allowing the slide to end its rearward motion, opening the breech and ejecting the empty cartridge case.
The chamber has 18 flutes that aid in the extraction process by allowing combustion gases to flow between the fired case and the chamber walls, preventing the case from "sticking" to the chamber walls. The drawback of this system is that the breech "opens" slightly prematurely to allow the slide to initiate its rearward motion. The high temperature gases cycling through a tube located below the chamber area and above the trigger made the early versions of this pistol uncomfortable to shoot after the content of two magazines were fired due to heating. The advantages of this system are a simpler manufacturing process due to the absence of a locking system and a high mechanical accuracy due to the barrel being fixed in the frame; the barrel does not execute any sort of lateral or vertical movement during the operating cycle as with the prolific Browning cam-action systems used extensively in other locked breech pistols.
The P7's spring extractor is contained within the slide, while the fixed ejector is a surface on the slide catch.
The grip of this pistol features a built-in cocking lever activated by gripping the pistol handle. Before the pistol can be fired, this lever must be squeezed. Thus this lever acts as a safety. The pistol has an innovative trigger (with a squeeze cocking lever located at the front of the grip, beneath the trigger guard) and is striker fired.[8] Squeezing the cocking lever with a force of 70 N (15.7 lbf) cocks the firing pin. Once fully depressed, only 2 pounds of force are required to keep the weapon cocked. The weapon is then fired by pressing the single stage trigger rated at approximately 20 N (4.5 lbf) As long as the lever is depressed, the weapon fires like any other semi-automatic pistol. If the lever is released, the weapon is immediately de-cocked and rendered safe. This method of operation dispensed the need for a manual safety selector while providing safety for the user carrying the pistol with a chambered round, and increased the speed with which the pistol could be deployed and fired. The trigger and firing mechanism's method of operation (and the unique slide catch) were protected by U.S. Patent 4,132,023, issued on January 2, 1979.
The P7 is fed from a single-stack box magazine with a capacity of 8 rounds, which is held inside the firearm's frame with a release located at the heel of the grip. After the last round has been fired, the slide will remain open thanks to a slide catch that can be released by pulling the slide further back or pressing the squeeze cocker.
The firearm uses a fixed, polygonal barrel (hexagonal with a 250 mm twist rate) and a fixed notched iron sight with contrast dots that enable shooting in low-level lighting conditions. The pistol is completely ambidextrous and two-handed use is enhanced through the use of a profiled and enlarged trigger guard.

title: For Sale:  Siamese (Thai) type 45 (1903) Mauser bayonet
postcontent:
Bayonets of this sort were produced from 1903 to 1908, in the Imperial Japanese Army Arsenal at Tokyo.

The ricasso, in Siamese characters, reads "RS121," which refers to the year Rattanakosin Sok 121, the 121st year of the Rattanakosin Era, which began in 1782 with the founding of Bangkok. The date equates to 1903 on the Gregorian calendar.

The serial number appears on the pommel, also in Thai script. 

This bayonet is in very good, rust free condition for being over 100 years old. 

A rare bayonet and tough to find for that collection of yours.

I will ship to anywhere in the lower 48 states for $12.00

Email me if you are interested or would like to make an offer.

title: For Sale:  -SOLD-  S&W M&P15 Custom Pink & White AR-15
location: South of Farmville, Greenville, North Carolina
postcontent:
Due to decent developments in Washington and the imminent re-enactment of the Federal Assault Weapons Ban, this gun just became a collector's item of sorts.
Since I have no idea if/when I'll be able to get another one, the price must go up to meet the demand.
Anyone who has already contacted me about this rifle will not be affected by the increase.

Anyone who's familiar with the AR-15/M4 platform will tell you that Mr. Stoner's design is pretty awesome. One of the things that makes it such a great platform is that it's all modular.
The downside of this is that after a while, they all start to look the same.
Not so with this one!
I started with a S&W M&P15 M4 configuration AR-15...then I went nuts... :)
The photos will give the full story, but I've outlined the highlights below.

- Custom Duracoat in Lady Pink and White. Every part of the gun was disassembled, cleaned, degreased, abrasive-basted to remove any contaminants, then sprayed with 2 coats of Duracoat in either pink or white
- Free floating carbine length quad rail. Rock solid attachment to receiver, no slop or wiggle.
- Badger tactical Charging Handle Latch for easy cocking with gloves or "in a hurry".
- Removable A2-style carry handle with sight

*Note: It's not visible in the photos, but there is something a little odd going on with the shell deflector. When I got it, it had these strange little "craters" in the surface. I was afraid it was a flaw in the receiver forging, so I sent it back to Smith & Wesson. They checked it out and told me it was just cosmetic and didn't affect the integrity of the receiver at all. It didn't bother me much, so I coated over it and moved on. I just thought you should know about it.

This would make an excellent gift for the lady shooter in your life, or for yourself if you want one of the only truly unique AR-15's in the country.
Don't believe me? Do a google search for "Pink and white AR-15", see how many hits you get. As far as I can tell, there's maybe 3-4 that look anything like this one, and a couple of those are Hello Kitty-themed. Huh?
When's the last time you searched for ANYTHING and didn't get a million hits on what you wanted?

The price is pretty firm, but I will consider partial trades for other firearms, mostly handguns or tactical-type long guns.

If you already have an AR, but would like yours Duracoated similar to this one, I can do it for $400.

I am able to accept credit cards as payment through Square, but they charge me 3.5%, so you'll have to pay that extra fee if you want to use a credit card.

title: For Sale:  Vintage 1918 Republic Model B Truck
postcontent:
My uncle, a long time collector and mechanic for 65 years, has decided to sell his 1918 Republic Model B, truck, which was made in Alma, Michigan. This truck was restored in 1980 and is in good running condition, the gas headlights & tail light work. Because of infrequent use, a separate 2 gallon gas tank was installed under the hood, which can be removed and use the original tank. The original gas tank is still in good usable condition with no rust. My uncle said they used good galvanizing back then.

Republic Motor Truck Company was one of the major suppliers trucks used by American troops during World War I, hauling anything from Colt 1911's to Winchester & Remington rifles. This Model B is unique in looks compared to other old IH International and Ford trucks of that time period. Basically, a motorized Conestoga wagon.

title: For Sale/Trade:  M1-Carbine Plainfield post-WW2 made of WW2 parts!  Decent Condition! .30 cal
location: New Port Richey, Tampa/St. Pete, Florida
postcontent:
I have a plainfield m1-carbine for sale. It shoots a .30 cal round. After WW2 there were tons of M1 Carbine parts left over. They were going to be scrapped until Plainfield Company bought them and made more M1-carbines out of the parts. Therefore all the parts are from WW2 but the actual rifle was assembled after WW2. Some consider this a ww2 rifle and some don't consider it a World War 2 rifle but either way, this particular rifle has a great history.
I do not have a magazine for it. The back sight is missing off it but I have a replacement back sight for the m1 that can be installed.
I havent installed it yet personally but it isnt too difficult to do. 
The magazines arent too expensive but will run you about $20. $450 obo on the m-1 carbine. Also have a ww1 british eddystone .303 drill practice rifle used to train soldiers in ww1. Asking $400 on that one or $800 for the pair obo.

Feel free to ask questions or email me for more pictures
God bless
